<br>
Still in her white nightdress, she climbed out of her bed and went to the window. Still night, and dark. She was wide awake, the nightmare having dissipated any fog of sleep that may have still clung to her. Luclin was nothing more than a crescent, as she looked out the window towards the source of the shrill wail. The stables. Brimstone was awake and agitated inside.<br>
<br>
Without bothering to get a robe, she made her way barefoot down the halls and outside. Normally she would have approached the horse in full armor, considering the hellion he had become. But the whinnies seemed urgent, frightened, and to lose time while dressing for battle would have taken too long. She did, however, grab River's sword, Reaver, from the wall. The steel glinted slightly in the little moonlight the quarter moon afforded as she made her way across the grass to the stable.<br>
<br>
