<br>
&quot;What's wrong?&quot; she asked the horse, half expecting it to answer. No answer except it dancing nervously. She reached out a hand tentatively towards the trembling horse, ready to pull back if it tried to bite like it usually did. But not tonight. Closer she drew.<br>
<br>
Contact, finally, after a year. She touched her hand to Brimstone's mane.<br>
<br>
Hot. She had forgotten after a year how unnaturally warm the horse's bodyheat was. She ran her hand through its mane as its prancing slowed and stopped. It snorted once and was still under her caress.<br>
<br>
&quot;What, you crazy horse?&quot; she repeated, brushing her hand through its mane. It moved closer to her, lowering its head under her moving fingers. Slowly it nuzzled against her arm. After all that time fighting the horse, she felt like crying. It was finally accepting her.<br>
<br>
She found herself swinging up onto its back before she registered she was doing it. No saddle, reins, anything, just climbed up on a stool, sword still in hand, and onto the stallion's back. She ran her hand again through its mane, surprised she had made that bold a move, but everything seemed controlled.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now, you want to canter out and....&quot; she began.<br>
<br>
Then, clearly, in her mind, she clearly heard the thoughts of the horse, as if it had spoken out loud in common.<br>
<br>
--NOW, HUMAN. LET'S SEE IF YOU CAN RIDE.--<br>
<br>
